WEBVTT

00:00:06.410 --> 00:00:09.330
PROFESSOR: All right, we've been
slogging our way through

00:00:09.330 --> 00:00:11.460
derivation of the
plane groups.

00:00:11.460 --> 00:00:15.400
And I think I'll do a few more,
because we'll stumble

00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:20.620
across some major tricks in
deriving a subfamily of them.

00:00:20.620 --> 00:00:26.440
But to not get lost in the
forest because of all the

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:30.090
trees, I have a set of notes.

00:00:30.090 --> 00:00:34.200
They are handwritten because my
secretary would resign if

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:38.200
she had to fit in all these
figures and subscripts and

00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:39.810
strange symbols.

00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:43.880
So, they are as neat as
I could make them.

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:47.350
Sorry to say that, in running
them through the Xerox machine

00:00:47.350 --> 00:00:50.530
in an attempt to get everything
on one sheet, some

00:00:50.530 --> 00:00:53.100
of the last lines got clipped.

00:00:53.100 --> 00:00:59.050
So I'll run these through again
and give you a copy

00:00:59.050 --> 00:01:01.180
that's minus those
truncations.

00:01:14.210 --> 00:01:14.500
All right.

00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:19.860
What we've been doing so far,
to have a brief reprise, was

00:01:19.860 --> 00:01:23.640
to take the symmetries, the 10
two-dimensional plane group

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:24.150
symmetries.

00:01:24.150 --> 00:01:28.410
And they were one-, two-,
three-, four-, or sixfold

00:01:28.410 --> 00:01:37.850
axes, a mirror plane,
2mm, 3m, 4mm, 6mm.

00:01:37.850 --> 00:01:39.100
So there are 10 of them.

00:01:41.330 --> 00:01:45.240
And these are the so-called
crystallographic point groups.

00:01:45.240 --> 00:01:50.330
Crystallographic because we
considered only those rotation

00:01:50.330 --> 00:01:52.790
axes that are compatible
with a lattice.

00:01:52.790 --> 00:01:55.360
And they are point groups
because they leave at least

00:01:55.360 --> 00:01:59.910
one point in space,
invariant--

00:01:59.910 --> 00:02:02.780
stays there rigidly fixed.

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:07.510
And they are groups because the
collection of operations

00:02:07.510 --> 00:02:11.130
that are present satisfies the
postulates of the mathematical

00:02:11.130 --> 00:02:14.020
entity called a group.

00:02:14.020 --> 00:02:18.190
We've then are in the process of
taking these 10 symmetries

00:02:18.190 --> 00:02:23.670
and adding them to the 5
two-dimensional lattices.

00:02:23.670 --> 00:02:34.480
The parallelogram net, the
rectangular, the centered

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:50.605
rectangular, and the square,
and the hexagonal.

00:02:53.230 --> 00:02:56.950
And clearly, we can't put each
of those point groups in every

00:02:56.950 --> 00:02:58.380
one of the lattices.

00:02:58.380 --> 00:03:02.550
For example, the lattice has to
be square for either 4 or

00:03:02.550 --> 00:03:08.110
4mm, so we would attempt to
place only those two of the 10

00:03:08.110 --> 00:03:11.480
point groups into
a square net.

00:03:11.480 --> 00:03:13.760
We've gone through quite
a few of them.

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:15.900
I won't bother to draw
the pattern of

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:16.980
the symmetry elements.

00:03:16.980 --> 00:03:19.680
But we put no symmetry
at all in the general

00:03:19.680 --> 00:03:21.250
parallelogram net.

00:03:21.250 --> 00:03:24.240
And that is plane group P1.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:26.310
Maybe I will draw the
figures, after all.

00:03:26.310 --> 00:03:32.340
P2 was a twofold axis dropped
into a net, which had to have

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:36.315
no specialized shape, simply
because a twofold [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:36.315 --> 00:03:41.150
axis requires nothing but a
lattice row if one translation

00:03:41.150 --> 00:03:42.400
is combined with it.

00:03:44.922 --> 00:03:52.060
The threefold axis could fit
into an equilateral net.

00:03:52.060 --> 00:03:59.590
And there's the threefold axis
we added to a lattice point.

00:03:59.590 --> 00:04:02.740
And we have two additional
threefold axes in the centers

00:04:02.740 --> 00:04:06.440
of those 2 equilateral
triangles, which each make up

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:08.350
half the cell.

00:04:08.350 --> 00:04:13.750
P4 was the square net.

00:04:13.750 --> 00:04:16.589
We put a fourfold axis at
the corner of the cell.

00:04:16.589 --> 00:04:18.680
We've got another one
in the middle.

00:04:18.680 --> 00:04:21.945
Two folds in the middle of
the edges because of the

00:04:21.945 --> 00:04:27.520
180-degree rotation that is
built into the fourfold axis.

00:04:27.520 --> 00:04:30.430
And P6.

00:04:30.430 --> 00:04:33.130
We put that into a
hexagonal net.

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:36.900
We've got sixfold axes that we
dropped in at the lattice

00:04:36.900 --> 00:04:39.430
point only, nothing else.

00:04:42.970 --> 00:04:46.430
There's a 120-degree rotation at
the lattice point, and that

00:04:46.430 --> 00:04:48.510
gives us the threefold
axes that are

00:04:48.510 --> 00:04:50.530
present in P3, as well.

00:04:50.530 --> 00:04:54.510
There's a 180-degree rotation
contained in a sixfold axis,

00:04:54.510 --> 00:04:59.180
and that gives us the twofold
axes in all of the

00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:00.430
locations of P2.

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:08.190
OK, I haven't drawn in any
representative patterns, but

00:05:08.190 --> 00:05:09.360
let me remind you again.

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:13.550
The pattern that is
characteristic of every one of

00:05:13.550 --> 00:05:17.610
the plane groups is just the
pattern that the point group

00:05:17.610 --> 00:05:20.460
that you've placed at the
lattice point would produce.

00:05:20.460 --> 00:05:23.810
And that pattern is, in turn,
hung at every lattice point of

00:05:23.810 --> 00:05:25.580
the two-dimensional cell.

00:05:25.580 --> 00:05:29.880
So even though the huge number
of symmetry elements that's

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:32.710
present in the higher symmetry
point groups is rather

00:05:32.710 --> 00:05:33.820
intimidating--

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:37.560
you say, wow, how would one
draw a pattern for that--

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:40.840
the pattern is nothing more
complicated than the pattern

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:43.530
of the symmetry that you've
placed at the lattice point.

00:05:43.530 --> 00:05:47.290
And all of these other symmetry
elements arise to

00:05:47.290 --> 00:05:51.280
express relations between the
motifs that you've placed at

00:05:51.280 --> 00:05:54.590
the initial representative
lattice point.

00:05:54.590 --> 00:05:57.220
Deriving these, we used one
theorem, which it's well to

00:05:57.220 --> 00:05:58.150
remind you of.

00:05:58.150 --> 00:06:04.050
And that is that if I have a
rotation operation A alpha,

00:06:04.050 --> 00:06:07.290
follow that by a translation
that's perpendicular to the

00:06:07.290 --> 00:06:10.730
rotation axis, what I get
is a new rotation

00:06:10.730 --> 00:06:12.790
operation is B alpha.

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:15.880
And it's located in a very
specific location.

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:20.650
And that is at a location that's
a distance x equal half

00:06:20.650 --> 00:06:23.050
the magnitude of the translation
times the

00:06:23.050 --> 00:06:26.570
cotangent of alpha over 2.

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:31.320
So this combination term, if
nothing else, reminds us that

00:06:31.320 --> 00:06:36.250
these combination theorems, as I
call them, are not equations

00:06:36.250 --> 00:06:37.890
in symmetry elements.

00:06:37.890 --> 00:06:41.680
They are equations in individual
operations.

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:46.160
So, for example, if I combine
the fourfold axis with the

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:50.750
translation, the 180-degree
operation that's present in a

00:06:50.750 --> 00:06:53.610
fourfold axis puts B pi here.

00:06:53.610 --> 00:06:58.650
The 90-degree rotation puts
B pi over 2 here.

00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:01.270
And the 270-degree rotation--

00:07:01.270 --> 00:07:04.750
which I can define just as well
as A minus pi over 2--

00:07:04.750 --> 00:07:07.950
puts the operation A minus
2 pi over 2 down here.

00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:10.480
So it's not an equation
in symmetry elements.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:12.960
It's an equation in individual
operations.

00:07:16.986 --> 00:07:20.680
Then some peculiarities started
to arise, which we

00:07:20.680 --> 00:07:23.930
perhaps might not think of.

00:07:23.930 --> 00:07:28.400
If we put a mirror plane in a
primitive rectangular net,

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:31.980
that gave a group that
we called Pm.

00:07:31.980 --> 00:07:36.180
If we combine that with a
translation, we need a theorem

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:42.590
that says what happens if you
combine a mirror reflection

00:07:42.590 --> 00:07:45.610
operation with a translation
that's perpendicular to it.

00:07:45.610 --> 00:07:48.370
We sketch that out, and once and
for all could decide that

00:07:48.370 --> 00:07:51.670
it's going to be a new
reflection operation that's

00:07:51.670 --> 00:07:58.010
located halfway along this
perpendicular translation.

00:07:58.010 --> 00:08:02.670
So this reflection operation
sigma, combined with this

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:06.830
translation, gave us a new
reflection operation, sigma

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:08.710
prime, halfway along the cell.

00:08:08.710 --> 00:08:10.440
And, of course, we have
this one hanging at a

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:13.340
lattice point as well.

00:08:13.340 --> 00:08:14.730
And then came the
interesting one.

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:17.920
When we combined a mirror plane
now with the centered

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:25.500
rectangular net, we have all of
the mirror planes that we

00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:28.590
have here, because this
primitive rectangular lattice

00:08:28.590 --> 00:08:30.745
is a subgroup of the
centered lattice.

00:08:30.745 --> 00:08:34.049
Then the interesting thing
happened when we combined the

00:08:34.049 --> 00:08:39.850
reflection operation sigma with
this translation that

00:08:39.850 --> 00:08:42.340
went to the center
of the cell.

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:45.600
And that gave us a
transformation that was

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:49.150
something we had not
encountered before.

00:08:49.150 --> 00:08:53.940
We took an object, reflected
it in this plane, and then

00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:56.030
translated it down
to a centered

00:08:56.030 --> 00:08:58.760
lattice point over here--

00:08:58.760 --> 00:09:01.440
to give us one that sat here--

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:07.005
and then asked, how did I get
from the first one, a

00:09:07.005 --> 00:09:10.020
right-handed one perhaps,
to a second one that's a

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:13.425
left-handed one, and then a
third left-handed one that

00:09:13.425 --> 00:09:14.890
sits down here?

00:09:14.890 --> 00:09:18.220
The answer is that we found
there was no way we could

00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:23.230
specify getting from number 1 to
number 3 in a single shot.

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:25.880
We had to take two
steps to do it.

00:09:25.880 --> 00:09:28.890
And there was nothing more
simple than that.

00:09:28.890 --> 00:09:34.020
We had to first translate
down by the part of the

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:34.880
translation--

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:35.920
let me call it tau--

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:39.870
which is equal to that part of
the translation t, which is

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:42.160
parallel to the reflection
operation.

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:46.430
And then we had to reflect
across, and that would get us

00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:47.920
from the first to the third.

00:09:47.920 --> 00:09:50.380
That was a new sort
of operation.

00:09:50.380 --> 00:09:53.670
We'd indicate its locus by a
dashed line to distinguish it

00:09:53.670 --> 00:09:54.860
from a mirror plane.

00:09:54.860 --> 00:09:58.760
And it has a translation part
and a reflection part.

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:00.650
Doesn't matter what order
in which we do them.

00:10:00.650 --> 00:10:03.787
We get to the same location if
we reflect first and then

00:10:03.787 --> 00:10:06.880
slide or slide first
and then reflect.

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:09.180
So this was a new operation
that I'll

00:10:09.180 --> 00:10:12.360
represent by sigma tau--

00:10:12.360 --> 00:10:14.790
looks sort of like a symbol
for reflection, but the

00:10:14.790 --> 00:10:17.990
subscript reminds us you've got
to translate by an amount

00:10:17.990 --> 00:10:22.050
tau that is parallel to the
initial mirror plane.

00:10:22.050 --> 00:10:26.010
And this gave us a new theorem
that a general translation

00:10:26.010 --> 00:10:29.020
that had a part t perpendicular
and a component

00:10:29.020 --> 00:10:33.520
t parallel, when it followed
a reflection operation, was

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:39.125
equal to a net effect of
reproducing the object by a

00:10:39.125 --> 00:10:41.220
glide plane, sigma tau prime.

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:44.840
It had tau equal to the part
of the translation that was

00:10:44.840 --> 00:10:48.540
parallel to the reflection
part of the locus.

00:10:48.540 --> 00:10:52.145
And it was located always at
one-half the perpendicular

00:10:52.145 --> 00:10:53.395
part of the translation.

00:10:56.910 --> 00:11:02.180
So using that theorem and
completing the mirror planes

00:11:02.180 --> 00:11:08.360
that hang at the lattice
points, we have a very

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:11.410
interesting group that consists
of a centered

00:11:11.410 --> 00:11:16.610
lattice, mirror plane hung at
the corner lattice point--

00:11:16.610 --> 00:11:19.965
this is also a lattice point,
so we automatically get the

00:11:19.965 --> 00:11:22.040
mirror plane in the middle
of the cell--

00:11:22.040 --> 00:11:27.260
and then in between, we get this
new 2-step operation, the

00:11:27.260 --> 00:11:29.050
glide plane.

00:11:29.050 --> 00:11:31.400
And the pattern that's
representative of this plane

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:35.960
group is, as advertised, just
what a mirror plane does.

00:11:35.960 --> 00:11:40.340
And that is hung at every
lattice point of the centered

00:11:40.340 --> 00:11:42.350
rectangular net.

00:11:42.350 --> 00:11:46.310
So the glide plane, this new
operation that popped up, does

00:11:46.310 --> 00:11:50.190
what the new operations
did in all of the

00:11:50.190 --> 00:11:51.950
other preceding groups.

00:11:51.950 --> 00:11:55.220
It tells you how do you get from
the pair that you've hung

00:11:55.220 --> 00:11:58.920
at the lattice point to
these that sit in the

00:11:58.920 --> 00:12:00.340
center of the cell.

00:12:00.340 --> 00:12:02.660
They're related by translation,
but the relation

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:05.910
of one to another of these
motifs is by the glide plane.

00:12:05.910 --> 00:12:10.270
So that is an operation which
has arisen in the group.

00:12:10.270 --> 00:12:14.840
And this, then, is a group
that we would call Cm.

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:18.210
C for a centered rectangular
net, as opposed to the

00:12:18.210 --> 00:12:21.255
primitive net, which is the one
we got immediately before.

00:12:24.450 --> 00:12:27.330
Again, I sound like a cracked
record sometimes, but let me

00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:30.160
emphasize the simplicity
of these patterns.

00:12:30.160 --> 00:12:35.140
Again, the pattern consists of
what you would get when you

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:39.730
hung a motif on one lattice
point, and then that is

00:12:39.730 --> 00:12:42.470
repeated by m, which is the
symmetry you've placed at a

00:12:42.470 --> 00:12:43.280
lattice point.

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:45.500
And that's hung at every lattice
point of the centered

00:12:45.500 --> 00:12:46.420
rectangular net.

00:12:46.420 --> 00:12:50.540
The glide planes just express
relations between things that

00:12:50.540 --> 00:12:53.580
you already have when you've
hung the motifs

00:12:53.580 --> 00:12:55.760
on the lattice point.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:13:00.740
Any questions after this
brief reprieve?

00:13:00.740 --> 00:13:01.980
Comments?

00:13:01.980 --> 00:13:02.545
Yes, sir.

00:13:02.545 --> 00:13:06.790
AUDIENCE: You called those
[INAUDIBLE] glides,

00:13:06.790 --> 00:13:08.990
that's a sigma tau?

00:13:08.990 --> 00:13:10.150
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:13:10.150 --> 00:13:12.220
The relation between
this one and this

00:13:12.220 --> 00:13:14.180
one, I've called sigma.

00:13:14.180 --> 00:13:16.050
That's the reflection
operation.

00:13:16.050 --> 00:13:19.290
The relation between this one
and this one down here would

00:13:19.290 --> 00:13:22.290
be the operation that has
a reflection part and a

00:13:22.290 --> 00:13:23.540
translation part, tau.

00:13:31.730 --> 00:13:36.630
Let me point out something
that's worth observing when we

00:13:36.630 --> 00:13:39.020
start making some more
complex additions.

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:50.220
We said early on that we only
have to consider translations

00:13:50.220 --> 00:13:52.920
that terminate within
the unit cell.

00:13:52.920 --> 00:13:57.570
Because everything is
translationally periodic--

00:13:57.570 --> 00:14:00.120
not only the atoms in the
motifs but the symmetry

00:14:00.120 --> 00:14:01.730
elements as well.

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:07.760
But the observation that I want
to make is that if we put

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:08.780
a glide plane in.

00:14:08.780 --> 00:14:13.340
And let's do that for the direct
addition of a glide

00:14:13.340 --> 00:14:16.070
plane to a lattice point.

00:14:16.070 --> 00:14:21.940
And having done that, we have
the potential of possibly

00:14:21.940 --> 00:14:24.941
having derived a group that
we would call Cg.

00:14:31.194 --> 00:14:31.680
OK.

00:14:31.680 --> 00:14:36.570
This diagonal translation--

00:14:36.570 --> 00:14:39.030
this is T1, and this is T2.

00:14:39.030 --> 00:14:41.850
We might ask, what is the
reflect [INAUDIBLE] glide

00:14:41.850 --> 00:14:44.980
operation that sits at the
origin lattice point, followed

00:14:44.980 --> 00:14:46.540
by T1 plus T2.

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:54.480
Well, what does our
theorem tell us?

00:14:54.480 --> 00:14:58.250
It says that we should get
a new glide plane.

00:14:58.250 --> 00:15:03.250
It should be at one-half of the
perpendicular part of the

00:15:03.250 --> 00:15:04.950
translation.

00:15:04.950 --> 00:15:07.720
And the perpendicular part
of the translation is T2.

00:15:11.250 --> 00:15:16.710
So this is at one-half of T2,
and it should have a glide

00:15:16.710 --> 00:15:18.880
component equal to the
parallel part of the

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:21.280
translation, and that is T1.

00:15:27.570 --> 00:15:31.780
T1 plus the original glide
component, tau.

00:15:31.780 --> 00:15:32.510
What is this?

00:15:32.510 --> 00:15:41.350
A glide component of half of
T1 plus the entire T1.

00:15:41.350 --> 00:15:45.060
If we ask, does that
make sense?

00:15:45.060 --> 00:15:51.360
Yeah, we would glide down to
here and then we would

00:15:51.360 --> 00:15:53.240
translate down to here.

00:15:53.240 --> 00:16:03.960
And that would give us sitting
at half of a path of T1, a new

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:05.280
object that sat here.

00:16:09.300 --> 00:16:13.935
Is that a glide operation?

00:16:16.445 --> 00:16:17.560
Yeah, it is.

00:16:17.560 --> 00:16:21.700
But it is one that is not really
distinct from the glide

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:23.210
plane that sits here.

00:16:23.210 --> 00:16:29.130
Because if we have a glide
operation with tau equal to

00:16:29.130 --> 00:16:34.310
one-half of T1, and if this
sits in a lattice, then

00:16:34.310 --> 00:16:39.020
there's going to be a glide
plane has tau equal to 1 plus

00:16:39.020 --> 00:16:41.410
one-half of T1.

00:16:41.410 --> 00:16:43.910
And there will have to be
another glide operation that

00:16:43.910 --> 00:16:47.380
consists of 2 plus
one-half of T1.

00:16:47.380 --> 00:16:49.920
And the reason is that
everything is periodic at an

00:16:49.920 --> 00:16:51.290
interval T1.

00:16:51.290 --> 00:16:56.660
So the moral that I'm trying to
draw here is that one can

00:16:56.660 --> 00:17:04.069
add or subtract to identify the

00:17:04.069 --> 00:17:06.589
actual nature of a symmetry.

00:17:06.589 --> 00:17:09.440
One can add or subtract
an integral number of

00:17:09.440 --> 00:17:10.690
translations.

00:17:19.560 --> 00:17:33.960
And that permits one to reduce
any tau to a sigma tau prime,

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:38.170
such that tau prime is always
less than the translation

00:17:38.170 --> 00:17:39.470
that's parallel to the tau.

00:17:39.470 --> 00:17:43.190
In other words, lop off this
translation of an entire T1,

00:17:43.190 --> 00:17:47.790
this translation of the entire
T2, and you have identified

00:17:47.790 --> 00:17:51.610
the basic nature of the glide
operation that sits here as

00:17:51.610 --> 00:17:54.830
something with a translation
that's half of T1.

00:17:54.830 --> 00:17:58.750
The translations that move
motifs out of the cell may be

00:17:58.750 --> 00:18:02.530
related by a glide operation
that involves an integral

00:18:02.530 --> 00:18:04.720
number of T1s plus half of T1.

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:08.290
But it doesn't change the basic
nature of the simplest

00:18:08.290 --> 00:18:10.450
glide step that's in there.

00:18:10.450 --> 00:18:12.950
That's a very obscure
