perpendicular and one-half of
one-half of the body diagonal.

00:35:40.570 --> 00:35:42.490
So it's one-quarter.

00:35:42.490 --> 00:35:45.170
All this equals one-quarter
of T1 plus T2.

00:35:58.690 --> 00:35:58.960
OK.

00:35:58.960 --> 00:36:02.480
Now something unexpected
happens.

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:08.770
If we would move along,
I skipped over 3m.

00:36:08.770 --> 00:36:11.690
We know what P3 looks like.

00:36:11.690 --> 00:36:20.420
And that is a hexagonal net,
an equilateral net.

00:36:20.420 --> 00:36:23.750
And we have a threefold axis
that we've added to the

00:36:23.750 --> 00:36:25.270
lattice point.

00:36:25.270 --> 00:36:29.020
And then we found additional
threefold axes in the center

00:36:29.020 --> 00:36:31.700
of these triangles.

00:36:31.700 --> 00:36:35.410
And, once again, the pattern
that has this symmetry is just

00:36:35.410 --> 00:36:40.310
a triangle of objects hung
at every lattice point.

00:36:40.310 --> 00:36:46.560
And now we want to add
a mirror plane to

00:36:46.560 --> 00:36:49.010
that threefold axis.

00:36:49.010 --> 00:36:57.240
So we have a primitive
equilateral net plus the

00:36:57.240 --> 00:37:05.560
two-dimensional plane
point group 3m.

00:37:05.560 --> 00:37:08.930
The question is, which
way should we

00:37:08.930 --> 00:37:10.220
orient the mirror plane?

00:37:13.890 --> 00:37:16.950
Well, a mirror plane says, I
want to be along the edge of

00:37:16.950 --> 00:37:19.110
either a centered rectangular
net or a

00:37:19.110 --> 00:37:20.760
primitive rectangular net.

00:37:20.760 --> 00:37:23.250
There's nothing about this
lattice that looks

00:37:23.250 --> 00:37:25.920
rectangular.

00:37:25.920 --> 00:37:27.346
Yeah, there is.

00:37:27.346 --> 00:37:30.020
I see a couple of people
doing this, and they

00:37:30.020 --> 00:37:32.460
have the right idea.

00:37:32.460 --> 00:37:33.560
Here's a lattice point.

00:37:33.560 --> 00:37:39.340
If we go more than one unit cell
in this diagram, here's a

00:37:39.340 --> 00:37:40.140
lattice point.

00:37:40.140 --> 00:37:41.120
Here's a lattice point.

00:37:41.120 --> 00:37:42.270
Here's a lattice point.

00:37:42.270 --> 00:37:43.740
Here's a lattice point.

00:37:43.740 --> 00:37:51.090
Go down to here and
go over to here.

00:37:51.090 --> 00:37:55.350
And lo and behold, here is a
centered rectangular net,

00:37:55.350 --> 00:37:58.320
hiding incognito in
a hexagonal net.

00:38:03.170 --> 00:38:04.010
Well, that helps.

00:38:04.010 --> 00:38:09.800
I can put in the mirror plane.

00:38:09.800 --> 00:38:12.680
But let me point out-- this is
getting very messy, so I'll

00:38:12.680 --> 00:38:14.090
redraw it on a smaller scale.

00:38:25.740 --> 00:38:30.825
This will be worth doing so that
it's perfectly obvious.

00:38:30.825 --> 00:38:35.155
I'm going to draw a number
of equilateral nets.

00:38:41.590 --> 00:38:43.880
The reason I'm drawing more than
one cell, I would like to

00:38:43.880 --> 00:38:49.640
point out that here is one
centered rectangular net.

00:38:49.640 --> 00:38:55.240
And it has its edge
perpendicular to the

00:38:55.240 --> 00:38:57.830
translations in the
hexagonal net.

00:38:57.830 --> 00:39:03.290
But there is also a rectangular
net that

00:39:03.290 --> 00:39:05.835
goes down like this.

00:39:10.870 --> 00:39:14.740
That's a centered rectangular
net that has its edge along

00:39:14.740 --> 00:39:18.790
one of edges of the unit cell.

00:39:18.790 --> 00:39:20.310
So I have two possibilities.

00:39:20.310 --> 00:39:23.340
One is to draw the rectangular
net like this.

00:39:23.340 --> 00:39:27.470
The other one is to draw the
rectangular net like this.

00:39:27.470 --> 00:39:31.500
And having confused you
thoroughly, let me simply draw

00:39:31.500 --> 00:39:33.415
this larger cell again.

00:39:37.550 --> 00:39:41.430
And say that I could, if I
wanted to, put the mirror

00:39:41.430 --> 00:39:47.210
planes in in these directions,
along the edges of the cell.

00:39:52.900 --> 00:39:53.470
OK.

00:39:53.470 --> 00:39:56.470
And in this case, if you're
convinced that there's a

00:39:56.470 --> 00:39:59.285
centered rectangular
net sitting there.

00:39:59.285 --> 00:40:02.220
Let me clean this up.

00:40:02.220 --> 00:40:04.970
And here's one mirror plane.

00:40:04.970 --> 00:40:07.300
60 degrees away is another
mirror plane.

00:40:07.300 --> 00:40:10.580
And there'll be another mirror
plane at this lattice point

00:40:10.580 --> 00:40:11.830
doing this.

00:40:15.130 --> 00:40:21.540
So now I've got 3m at every one
of these threefold axes.

00:40:21.540 --> 00:40:27.175
And I got all those simply by
repeating these mirror planes

00:40:27.175 --> 00:40:28.380
by translation.

00:40:28.380 --> 00:40:31.940
But in one case, the mirror
planes are perpendicular to

00:40:31.940 --> 00:40:33.120
the cell edge.

00:40:33.120 --> 00:40:37.350
This being T1, let's say,
and this being T2.

00:40:37.350 --> 00:40:39.600
In this case, the mirror
planes are along the

00:40:39.600 --> 00:40:41.350
edges of the cell.

00:40:41.350 --> 00:40:46.000
This being T1, and
this being T2.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:46.880
So, holy mackerel!

00:40:46.880 --> 00:40:49.220
One point group.

00:40:49.220 --> 00:40:53.220
Two different space groups,
which differ in the way in

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:57.845
which the symmetry is oriented
relative to the lattice.

00:41:00.470 --> 00:41:03.370
And if you think back a little
bit, this particular net, with

00:41:03.370 --> 00:41:06.790
this dimensional specialization,
was happy with

00:41:06.790 --> 00:41:11.840
a sixfold access as well, and
will be compatible with 6mm.

00:41:11.840 --> 00:41:14.825
So, really, these two different
orientations for the

00:41:14.825 --> 00:41:17.600
mirror planes, even though we
haven't got there yet, are the

00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:20.120
two different orientations
which are both present

00:41:20.120 --> 00:41:24.970
simultaneously if we were
to put 6mm into

00:41:24.970 --> 00:41:27.720
this hexagonal net.

00:41:27.720 --> 00:41:30.090
So, same point group.

00:41:30.090 --> 00:41:31.530
Same lattice.

00:41:31.530 --> 00:41:35.430
Two different plane groups that
depend on the orientation

00:41:35.430 --> 00:41:37.490
of the symmetry relative
to the lattice.

00:41:40.680 --> 00:41:43.250
So there isn't even a one-to-one
correspondence

00:41:43.250 --> 00:41:46.045
between the point groups
and the plane groups.

00:41:49.280 --> 00:41:54.340
The pattern for either of these
is, once again, going to

00:41:54.340 --> 00:41:58.870
be just what the pattern of
the point group does.

00:41:58.870 --> 00:42:03.120
If we start with a motif here
and repeat that by the

00:42:03.120 --> 00:42:07.640
threefold axis and the mirror
planes, we would

00:42:07.640 --> 00:42:14.250
have motifs like this.

00:42:14.250 --> 00:42:21.560
And here the translation points
out in between the

00:42:21.560 --> 00:42:22.890
mirror planes.

00:42:22.890 --> 00:42:27.060
In this case, the mirror
planes would repeat the

00:42:27.060 --> 00:42:29.495
objects in two locations,
like this.

00:42:35.890 --> 00:42:38.290
So, indeed, both patterns
have 3mm symmetry.

00:42:38.290 --> 00:42:41.600
And what's different is the way
the translations come out

00:42:41.600 --> 00:42:44.780
in between those
mirror planes.

00:42:44.780 --> 00:42:44.990
OK.

00:42:44.990 --> 00:42:49.300
Now our notation has come
up against an impasse.

00:42:49.300 --> 00:42:55.040
We said that the notation for
the plane group should be the

00:42:55.040 --> 00:42:58.250
symbol for the lattice type,
which the initiated know has

00:42:58.250 --> 00:43:01.300
to be a hexagonal net.

00:43:01.300 --> 00:43:04.350
The point group that we've
added, which is 3m, but now

00:43:04.350 --> 00:43:08.873
how do we distinguish the two
different orientations of the

00:43:08.873 --> 00:43:10.150
mirror planes?

00:43:10.150 --> 00:43:16.630
And the way around that is to
actually use three symbols.

00:43:16.630 --> 00:43:22.420
And the second symbol
will be what is

00:43:22.420 --> 00:43:24.320
perpendicular to the cell edge.

00:43:28.870 --> 00:43:30.560
And the third symbol
will be what's

00:43:30.560 --> 00:43:32.180
parallel to the cell edge.

00:43:36.610 --> 00:43:39.325
So this one would
be called P3M1.

00:43:42.250 --> 00:43:45.330
And this one, just to
distinguish it, would be

00:43:45.330 --> 00:43:48.060
called P31M.

00:43:48.060 --> 00:43:50.900
So if this weren't bad enough,
now you've got almost the same

00:43:50.900 --> 00:43:55.590
symbol with a permutation of
two of the terms in it.

00:43:55.590 --> 00:43:59.920
In this case, the mirror plane
is along the cell edge along

00:43:59.920 --> 00:44:01.270
the translations.

00:44:01.270 --> 00:44:02.720
In this case, it's
perpendicular.

00:44:09.100 --> 00:44:14.042
But we're not quite yet done,
because we've got translations

00:44:14.042 --> 00:44:17.460
that are inclined to
mirror planes.

00:44:17.460 --> 00:44:21.580
And now you can see how prudent
I was in saying quite

00:44:21.580 --> 00:44:24.090
generally, without trying to
figure out what is the

00:44:24.090 --> 00:44:27.220
perpendicular part and what is
the parallel part, here's a

00:44:27.220 --> 00:44:31.920
translation and it's at an
angle to a mirror plane.

00:44:31.920 --> 00:44:38.580
And therefore we get a glide
that has to be halfway between

00:44:38.580 --> 00:44:40.030
these mirror planes.

00:44:40.030 --> 00:44:42.490
And there'll have to be a glide
halfway between these

00:44:42.490 --> 00:44:45.750
mirror planes, and a glide
that's halfway between these

00:44:45.750 --> 00:44:47.150
mirror planes.

00:44:47.150 --> 00:44:50.060
In this case, the mirror
planes are this way.

00:44:50.060 --> 00:44:52.980
Again, a translation that's
inclined to the mirror plane.

00:44:52.980 --> 00:44:56.630
We have to have a glide
that is midway between

00:44:56.630 --> 00:44:58.070
these mirror planes.

00:44:58.070 --> 00:45:02.850
In this case, they're a little
easier to identify.

00:45:02.850 --> 00:45:06.450
They sort of make a triangular
box that surrounds the

00:45:06.450 --> 00:45:09.230
threefold axis.

00:45:09.230 --> 00:45:16.390
So now we see another difference
in the plane groups

00:45:16.390 --> 00:45:18.390
and the reason why they're
so very distinct.

00:45:18.390 --> 00:45:22.010
And that is the rearrangement of
the glides relative to the

00:45:22.010 --> 00:45:24.560
threefold axes are quite
different in these two cases.

00:45:28.570 --> 00:45:30.500
So these are two quite
different symmetries.

00:45:30.500 --> 00:45:35.560
Notice that when we start
identifying special locations

00:45:35.560 --> 00:45:38.910
in these two plane groups, here
there is a location only

00:45:38.910 --> 00:45:43.520
of symmetry 3mm for a point
group, 3m for a point group.

00:45:43.520 --> 00:45:46.560
Here there are two different
locations, one that's symmetry

00:45:46.560 --> 00:45:50.240
3m, the other one is
just symmetry 3.

00:45:50.240 --> 00:45:54.720
So this is location of point
group 3 and a location of

00:45:54.720 --> 00:45:56.940
point group 3m.

00:45:56.940 --> 00:45:59.960
So the sort of special positions
that exist in these

00:45:59.960 --> 00:46:02.610
two plane groups will be
very, very different.

00:46:20.720 --> 00:46:24.010
One more addition, and then I
think we can leave with a

00:46:24.010 --> 00:46:25.950
light heart because
we should be done.

00:46:30.350 --> 00:46:35.190
What about a primitive
hexagonal net

00:46:35.190 --> 00:46:38.980
combined with 6mm?

00:46:38.980 --> 00:46:40.880
And if you think I'm going
to try to draw

00:46:40.880 --> 00:46:42.730
that, you're crazy.

00:46:42.730 --> 00:46:46.410
But I can say quite simply and
hopefully convince you that

00:46:46.410 --> 00:46:57.410
this looks like P31M plus P3M1
right on top of one another,

00:46:57.410 --> 00:47:01.370
because we've got mirror
planes that

00:47:01.370 --> 00:47:03.830
are 30 degrees apart.

00:47:03.830 --> 00:47:09.840
So, as a schematic direction and
an invitation to do this

00:47:09.840 --> 00:47:15.030
at home in your spare time, is
to take what P6 looks like.

00:47:21.080 --> 00:47:23.130
And that's sixfold axes
at the lattice points.

00:47:23.130 --> 00:47:24.660
Threefolds here.

00:47:24.660 --> 00:47:28.010
Twofolds here.

00:47:28.010 --> 00:47:31.060
And then, directly on top of
this, place the mirrors and

00:47:31.060 --> 00:47:33.910
glides in this orientation, and
the mirrors and glides in

00:47:33.910 --> 00:47:35.090
this orientation.

00:47:35.090 --> 00:47:42.200
So we will have mirror planes
coming out like that, and

00:47:42.200 --> 00:47:47.230
glide planes in between all the
parallel mirror planes.

00:47:47.230 --> 00:47:52.910
As I say, I'm heroic
but not foolish.

00:47:52.910 --> 00:47:53.305
Yes.

00:47:53.305 --> 00:47:55.110
AUDIENCE: Can you just explain
that derivation again?

00:47:55.110 --> 00:47:56.990
Your P3 [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:56.990 --> 00:47:58.880
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:47:58.880 --> 00:48:04.380
The object of this additional
bit of confusion is to put in

00:48:04.380 --> 00:48:08.180
the symbol the point group,
which is 3m, and then tell you

00:48:08.180 --> 00:48:11.600
how the mirror plane in a
point group is oriented

00:48:11.600 --> 00:48:15.090
relative to the edges
of the cell.

00:48:15.090 --> 00:48:18.410
And we could call them anything
we wanted to.

00:48:18.410 --> 00:48:22.590
We could call them P3M
perpendicular, subscript

00:48:22.590 --> 00:48:23.580
perpendicular.

00:48:23.580 --> 00:48:26.970
Or P3M subscript parallel to
indicate mirror plane parallel

00:48:26.970 --> 00:48:30.010
to the cell edge.

00:48:30.010 --> 00:48:32.050
And mirror plane perpendicular
to the cell edge.

00:48:32.050 --> 00:48:35.840
Or we could call them some
obscenity, which would be very

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:37.580
descriptive, as well.

00:48:37.580 --> 00:48:41.660
But this is just a way of
keeping track of what's

00:48:41.660 --> 00:48:43.210
parallel to the cell
edge and what's

00:48:43.210 --> 00:48:44.460
perpendicular to the cell edge.

00:48:47.100 --> 00:48:51.510
So, this middle symbol is what's
oriented perpendicular

00:48:51.510 --> 00:48:52.600
to the cell edge.

00:48:52.600 --> 00:48:55.910
And in this case, this is the
mirror plane and that is

00:48:55.910 --> 00:48:56.820
perpendicular.

00:48:56.820 --> 00:48:59.460
All the mirror planes are
perpendicular to the

00:48:59.460 --> 00:49:01.920
edges of the cell.

00:49:01.920 --> 00:49:04.770
And then parallel to the
cell edge, there's

00:49:04.770 --> 00:49:07.350
no symmetry at all.

00:49:07.350 --> 00:49:08.500
So that's 1.

00:49:08.500 --> 00:49:10.020
1 stands for no symmetry.

00:49:10.020 --> 00:49:14.050
In this case, the mirror plane
is along the cell edge, so

00:49:14.050 --> 00:49:16.520
there's an M in the
third position.

00:49:16.520 --> 00:49:19.360
And perpendicular to the
cell edge, there's

00:49:19.360 --> 00:49:21.130
no symmetry at all--

00:49:21.130 --> 00:49:22.380
no symmetry plane at all.

00:49:25.500 --> 00:49:31.690
So it's purely arbitrary, but
we need some mechanism for

00:49:31.690 --> 00:49:34.380
distinguishing which one
we're talking about.

00:49:34.380 --> 00:49:36.750
That pretty much works
as well as anything.

00:49:36.750 --> 00:49:39.570
And it's a minor perturbation
of what we've done for the

00:49:39.570 --> 00:49:41.520
additional plane
group symbols.

00:49:46.900 --> 00:49:47.100
All right.

00:49:47.100 --> 00:49:51.956
It's time for our midafternoon
break.

00:49:51.956 --> 00:49:55.020
It's a nice place to quit,
because you're probably

00:49:55.020 --> 00:49:55.680
feeling good.

00:49:55.680 --> 00:49:59.530
We've done this, and we can
move on to something new.

00:49:59.530 --> 00:50:01.460
Actually, there's
one more trick.

00:50:01.460 --> 00:50:04.810
And unless you were really
clever, you wouldn't have

00:50:04.810 --> 00:50:05.730
thought of it.

00:50:05.730 --> 00:50:09.510
But there's another small family
of plane groups that we

00:50:09.510 --> 00:50:12.510
can get through one
particular device.

00:50:12.510 --> 00:50:14.420
I shouldn't have told you that,
because you'll be less

00:50:14.420 --> 00:50:15.860
inclined to come back now.

00:50:15.860 --> 00:50:17.730
But we're almost through.

00:50:17.730 --> 00:50:20.630
And I think it'll be very clear
what these additional

00:50:20.630 --> 00:50:21.880
possibilities are.